{{other uses|Adventus (disambiguation)}} {{Coin image box 1 double | header = | image = Image:Decius Adventus.jpg | caption_left = '''[[Obverse and reverse|O:]]''' draped and [[cuirass]]ed bust with [[radiate crown]] of [[Trajan Decius]] [[Imperator|IMP]] [[Gaius (name)|C]] [[Messius|M]] [[Quintus|Q]] [[Trajan Decius|TRAIANVS DECIVS]] [[Augustus (honorific)|AVG]] | caption_right = '''[[Obverse and reverse|R:]]''' [[Trajan Decius]] [[riding horse]], raising hand and holding [[scepter]] ADVENTVS [[Augustus (honorific)|AVG]] | width = 400 | footer = [[silver]] [[antoninianus]] struck in [[Rome]] 250 AD; ref.: RIC 11b; RSC 4 This coin was struck to the occasion of emperor's return (adventus) to Rome. | position = right | margin = 4 }}The '''adventus''' was a ceremony in [[ancient Rome]], in which an [[Roman emperor|emperor]] was formally welcomed into a city either during a progress or after a military campaign, often (but not always) Rome. The term is also used to refer to artistic depictions (usually in [[relief sculpture]], including coins) of such ceremonies.<ref name="MacCormack1974">{{cite book|author=Sabine MacCormack|title=Adventus and Consecratio: Studies in Roman Imperial Art and Panegyric from the Late Third to the Sixth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L02FXwAACAAJ|year=1974|publisher=University of Oxford}}</ref> Its 'opposite' is the ''[[profectio]]''.<ref name="EwaldNoreña2010">{{cite book|author1=Björn C. Ewald|author2=Carlos F. Noreña|title=The Emperor and Rome: Space, Representation, and Ritual|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tXzO4b2Z-44C&pg=PA40|date=2 December 2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-51953-3|pages=40–}}</ref>
For comparable ceremonies in Medieval and Early Modern Europe, sometimes employing consciously 'Roman' iconology, see [[Royal entry]].
