{{Infobox observatory |name = |background = |image = |caption = |organization = Mid Atlantic Star Party (MASP) |code = |location = [[Robbins, North Carolina]] |coords = {{Coord|35.436609|-79.550319|region:US-NC_type:landmark|display=inline,title|name=Site of Mid Atlantic Star Party observational astronomy event}} |altitude = 472' |weather = Variable weather - clear dark night skies |established = {{Start date|1995|10|01}} |closed = |website = [http://masp.us Mid Atlantic Star Party] |telescope1_name = |telescope1_type = |telescope2_name = |telescope2_type = |telescope3_name = |telescope3_type = |telescope4_name = |telescope4_type = }} The '''Mid Atlantic Star Party''' ('''MASP''') was an annual regional gathering of amateur [[astronomer]]s ([[star party]]) held each fall around October near [[Robbins, North Carolina]].
==History== First held in 1995, MASP is located in one of the darkest spots along the eastern U.S. coast and is the largest annual gathering of amateur astronomers between [[Vermont]]'s [[Stellafane]] and [[Florida]]'s [[Winter Star Party]].<ref name="masp">{{cite web |url=http://masp.us/about.htm |title=About MASP |accessdate=2007-03-23 |work=Mid-Atlantic Star Party }}</ref>
==Modern times== With attendance usually numbering in the hundreds,<ref name="nytmes">{{cite news |first=S. Kirk |last=Walsh |title= AHEAD; Star Parties |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=travel&res=9F05EFD91730F930A1575AC0A9639C8B63&n=Top%2FNews%2FScience%2FTopics%2FAstronomy%20and%20Astrophysics |work=New York Times |date=23 September 2005 |accessdate=2007-03-23 }}</ref> MASP was held at the [[Scouting in North Carolina|Occoneechee Council]] [[Boy Scout camp]] for the first decade of operation before scheduling conflicts forced a site change.<ref name="pilot1">{{cite news|first=John |last=Chappell |title=Robbins Seeks New Site for Star Party |url=http://www.thepilot.com/stories/20060907/news/local/20060907notebook.html |work=Southern Pines Pilot |date=7 September 2006 |accessdate=2007-03-23 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name="pilot2">{{cite news|first=John |last=Chappell |title=Robbins Star Party Here to Stay |url=http://www.thepilot.com/stories/20060908/news/local/20060908star.html |work=Southern Pines Pilot |date=12 September 2006 |accessdate=2007-03-23 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The star party has become a focus of the town of Robbins' economic and cultural planning process<ref name="pilot3">{{cite news|first=John |last=Chappell |title=Robbins Sets Plans For STEP |url=http://www.thepilot.com/stories/20061017/news/local/20061017step.html |work=Southern Pines Pilot |date=17 October 2006 |accessdate=2007-03-23 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> and has spurred the creation of a regional "dark park" to control [[light pollution]].<ref name="darkpark">{{cite web |url=http://darkpark.org/ |title=Dark Park |accessdate=2007-03-23 |work=DarkPark.Org }}</ref>
[[Image:2001panoramabg.jpg|thumb|center|700px|A panoramic view of the main observing field at the 2001 Mid Atlantic Star Party during the day.]]
